default9. defaultShould the government take any further any specific actions in relation to coolingdefault? defaultWe know that DECC are opposed to the idea of subsidising cooling by air conditioning: we are very much in sympathy with the idea that standard air conditioning should not be encouraged – because there are large carbon emission implications. This is because
default the standard approach to cooling – heat exchange with hot air – is expensive in electricity [and therefore carbon emissions].  
defaultHowever in warmer parts of Europe (and the World) where building cooling is recognised as being important to maintaining productivity, considerable work has been invested in developing Renewable Energy driven cooling systems and in balancing heating and co
defaultoling loads which if correctly executed can be the most energy efficient solution. Thermal Energy storage is at the heart of the systems and in this context providing heating can be considered as recharging the store with coolth and cooling as recharging t
defaulthe store with warmth.  In either case the heat is moved and stored rather than created.
defaultThe CoP (Coefficient of Performance) of a roof-mounted chiller can be as low as 1.5 on a hot day [1 kilowatt of electricity is needed to provide 1.5 kW of cooling].  Ho
defaultwever, some cooling is necessary, and there is a very much more effective way of achieving this – by employing ground source energy and allowing heat to escape to cold ground instead of forcing heat into hot air.  The CoP of “free cooling” (heat exchange w
defaultith cold ground by means of a circulation pump) can be as high as 25. The CoP of Renewable Cooling (heat exchange with cold ground assisted by a reversible heat pump) can 
defaultfrequently achieve a CoP of 8.
default Further this has the additional benefit of improving h
defaulteating CoP the following winter as the ground has been recharged and is therefore warmer. Improvements in heating CoP can be dramatic lifting the annual heating CoP from around 4 to around 5 in many cases.
default 
defaultThe carbon emission savings of using Renewable Co
defaultoling, instead of standard Air Conditioning, are huge and we believe that DECC will come to see that these should be encouraged
default as part of the fight to reduce carbon emissions
default.
defaultThere will need to be appropriate safeguards, which could be defined in terms o
defaultf requiring a high CoP before Renewable Cooling is recognised and requiring a high temperature set point so that Cooling is only used when necessary (rather than as an indulgence).
defaultDECC has been inclined to reject subsidy for renewable cooling as their int
defaulterpretation of the Renewable Energy Directive (RED) is that it would not count as “renewable” although it would save significant CO2 emissions. We think that DECC, which frequently claims that the RHI is a “world first”, should be making the case to Brusse
defaultls, rather than following DECC’s own timid interpretation of the RED.
